      <section class="bg-white rounded-lg shadow-md p-8 mb-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-[#071059] mb-4">Start with Decluttering for an Easier Derby Move</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
          The quickest way to speed up <strong>Derby removals</strong> is to pack less. Do one sweep per room: keep, donate, recycle, bin.
          Fewer items means fewer boxes, less lifting, and a faster load/unload.
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 text-gray-700 space-y-2">
          <li>Set a 20-minute timer per room to avoid overthinking.</li>
          <li>Bag up “not used in 12 months” items for donation.</li>
          <li>Sell bulky furniture early to reduce moving-day logistics.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="bg-white rounded-lg shadow-md p-8 mb-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-[#071059] mb-4">Use the Right Boxes and Pack Smart by Weight</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
          Heavy boxes are the #1 cause of breakages and sore backs. In 2026, the “pro rule” still wins:
          <strong>heavy items in small boxes</strong>, <strong>light items in big boxes</strong>.
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 text-gray-700 space-y-2">
          <li>Books, tools, and kitchenware go in small/medium boxes.</li>
          <li>Linens and clothes go in large boxes (or bags) to keep weight down.</li>
          <li>Keep a “one-person lift” limit — if you struggle, it’s too heavy.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="bg-white rounded-lg shadow-md p-8 mb-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-[#071059] mb-4">Keep Clothes Wrinkle-Free with Garment Hacks</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
          For quick <strong>removals in Derby</strong>, don’t fold everything. Keep clothes on hangers and protect them in bundles.
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 text-gray-700 space-y-2">
          <li>Group 10–15 hangers and slide a bin bag over them (tie at the hook).</li>
          <li>Use wardrobe boxes for suits, dresses, and coats if you have them.</li>
          <li>Roll t-shirts and gym wear to save space and reduce creasing.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="bg-white rounded-lg shadow-md p-8 mb-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-[#071059] mb-4">Label Boxes with Codes Instead of Contents</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
          Writing “TV” or “Jewellery” on a box advertises valuables. Use a simple colour or code system instead:
          <strong>KIT</strong> (kitchen), <strong>BED1</strong>, <strong>OFF</strong>, etc.
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 text-gray-700 space-y-2">
          <li>Put the code on <strong>two sides</strong> and the <strong>top</strong> for fast spotting.</li>
          <li>Keep a note on your phone that maps codes to rooms.</li>
          <li>Add “FRAG” for fragile items without naming what’s inside.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="bg-white rounded-lg shadow-md p-8 mb-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-[#071059] mb-4">Tape Doors and Drawers Securely Shut</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
          Wardrobe doors swinging open and drawers sliding out cause damage in transit. Secure them before the van is loaded.
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 text-gray-700 space-y-2">
          <li>Use painter’s tape on finished surfaces to avoid sticky residue.</li>
          <li>For heavier units, use stretch wrap around the entire piece.</li>
          <li>Remove delicate handles if they snag or loosen easily.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="bg-white rounded-lg shadow-md p-8 mb-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-[#071059] mb-4">Bag Screws from Dismantled Furniture</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
          Losing one screw can delay reassembly. Bag screws/bolts per item and attach them to the furniture.
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 text-gray-700 space-y-2">
          <li>Use zip bags and label them: “BED FRAME”, “TV UNIT”, “DESK”.</li>
          <li>Tape the bag to the underside of the item (or keep in a toolbox).</li>
          <li>Snap a photo of how it fits together for easy rebuilding.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="bg-white rounded-lg shadow-md p-8 mb-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-[#071059] mb-4">Pack Fragile Items with Extra Padding</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
          Glassware and ceramics need padding and smart stacking. Use towels, soft clothes, and paper to protect edges and corners.
          If you’re short on time, our team can provide <a href="/services/packing-services/" class="underline underline-offset-2 font-medium">professional packing services</a>.
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 text-gray-700 space-y-2">
          <li>Pack plates vertically like records for better shock resistance.</li>
          <li>Fill all gaps — movement inside the box causes breakages.</li>
          <li>Mark boxes “FRAG” and keep them on top during loading.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="bg-white rounded-lg shadow-md p-8 mb-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-[#071059] mb-4">Create an Essentials Box for First Night</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
          Whether you’re using <strong>removal companies in Derby</strong> or packing solo, an essentials box stops you ripping open
          20 cartons at 10pm.
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 text-gray-700 space-y-2">
          <li>Kettle, mugs, tea/coffee, snacks, bin bags, toilet roll.</li>
          <li>Chargers, extension lead, torch, basic tools, scissors.</li>
          <li>Bedding, toiletries, and a change of clothes.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="bg-white rounded-lg shadow-md p-8 mb-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-[#071059] mb-4">Use Vacuum Bags to Maximise Space</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
          Vacuum bags are a 2026 staple for big, soft items like duvets, pillows, and winter coats — they reduce volume fast.
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 text-gray-700 space-y-2">
          <li>Label bags by room so unpacking stays simple.</li>
          <li>Keep one bag for “seasonal” items you won’t need immediately.</li>
          <li>Don’t over-compress delicate feather/down items for long periods.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

